name: The Suite: Private Room + Kitchenette
description:
The Suite at Chestnut Cottage is a cosy 2-room suite that sleeps 1 or 2 people with space to lounge/dine in the adjoining private kitchenette. We are minutes from downtown, in the friendly, walkable Wolseley neighbourhood.

Note: We don’t accept 3rd party bookings and our accommodations don’t have a shower (coming June ‘25), stove, oven or TV.
neighborhood_overview: Wolseley is a mixed neighbourhood of early 20th-century detached wood frame houses on elm-lined streets amid a scattering of small businesses and character apartment buildings. We are 5 minutes by bus or car, and less than 20 minutes on foot from downtown Winnipeg, the University of Winnipeg, Health Sciences Centre and Misericordia Health Centre. We are no more than 20 to 25 minutes by cab, bus or car from the University of Manitoba and most other destinations in the city. Several local grocery stores, coffee shops, bakeries, restaurants and other shops are within a 5-minute walk and major shopping is close by.
host_about:
We are two women living in a century home in the Wolseley neighbourhood in central Winnipeg. One designer and one carpenter by trade, we love collaborating on the restoration of this old house, making it a home for ourselves and a restful home-away-from-home for travellers.

We also enjoy travelling the world, and exploring rural North America in our vintage 1959 Sprite caravan.

Whether it’s in our home or on the road, we hope to see you soon!

name: Studio close to Forks, Museum, Downtown & Park
description:
This cozy Studio on 2nd floor above my home has a private entrance & large sunny balcony. Ideal for couples or freinds with one queen and a floor matress if needed.
The yard with unique Flowers, Plants and Berries is home to Birds & Pollinators.
The sought after neighbor is surrounded by Park and Rivers yet only 3 mins by car or 20 mins walking to City Center.
Local Amenities include: Pubs, Restaurants, Library, Museum, Baseball Stadium, The Forks, and a Historic Fort.
neighborhood_overview:
Located in lovely Saint Boniface, the French quater.
Many fine restaurants, cafes and even a fancy chocolate maker just down the street.
The New Humans Rights Musem, The Forks and Downtown are reachable via a riverside parkway and the amazing Esplande pedestrian bridge. St Bee pub/beer vendor and Le Garage pub/restaurant are very close if you need a pint or like live music.
host_about:
I planted trees for a living. Across Canada, Ive hand planted more then 2 million over the years (hopefully Ive offset all the air travel I do :)
I surf, snowboard, bike and hike anywhere I can
I continue to backpack, revisiting places like India, Bali, Malaysia, Hawaii, Portugal, Sri Lanka, Morrocco repeatedly
I believe in local food sources and am currently building a passivley heated greenhouse/garage.
Im a gatherer and make wine from things suchs as : apples, rhubarb, hisbiscus, raspberries and saskatoon(service) berries.
Im happy to share my local and global knowledge specially if its over a glass of my wine!

The south part of Osborne Street cuts a line between these two neighbourhoods, which are some of the oldest residential areas of Winnipeg. Sandwiched between these abodes is a street chock full of fantastic casual eateries, along with The Park Theatre, arguably Winnipeg’s busiest venues for live music film and artsy happenings. name: modern 2 bedroom in South Osborne
description: You are steps away from all amenities and Winnipeg's active transportation
neighborhood_overview:
South Osborne is where you can access the verdant, riverside parklands of Kingston Row where, come winter, you can make your way down to the end of the Red River Mutual Trail for some serious skating and winter fun. In the summer, enjoy legendary desserts like the "goog special" (a blueberry milkshake topped with banana ice cream and hot fudge) which have made the Bridge Drive-In one of Winnipeg’s most renowned locales for more than 50 years. This walk-up summertime ice cream spot is just a short stroll from the pedestrian Elm Park Bridge and sees vast line-ups throughout the season.

In recent years, a handful of new shops and eateries have also opened in the area. At Chaeban Ice Cream, enjoy small batch, naturally made ice cream in incredible flavours like Abir Al Sham, a traditional Syrian recipe with rose water, orange blossom, toasted pistachios, ricotta cheese, and orchid root powder. Enjoy all the amenities downtown living has to offer, and in an extremely convenient and modern location that includes free underground heated parking.
The MTS Center, The Forks, Polo Park, The Exchange District and Osborne Village are all within just a few minutes drive or walk.
neighborhood_overview:
Only minutes away from CBC Radio and University of Winnipeg. This loft-style condo is ideal for the young professional and student alike. It can sleep up to 3 guests, or it can be a luxurious space for 1 - 2.

Directly adjacent to the building as well, and within a 5 minute walk you will find dozens of great restaurants ranging from pubs, to sushi, to thai food - Whatever peaks your taste-buds' interest on that given night.

Only 5 minute bus/cab/car ride away is the MTS center (Go Jets!) and 5 minutes further from that is the Exchange District with all of Winnipeg's most popular nightlife bars/pubs/nightclubs etc. Feel free to ask me which scene may be more suitable for you and your guests as I'm very familiar with all of them and most of their management.
host_about:
With many years of experience and positive reviews on my side, I take pride in being an approachable, responsive, and courteous Superhost. 

I look forward to hosting you - I work alongside owners, and other professional Airbnb companies in order to deliver the best possible experience to the guest. 

Please don't hesitate to reach out if you have any questions about any of my listings.

We hope to host you soon.

neighborhood_overview:
St. John's is one of the more established neighbourhoods of the North End, its development occurring shortly after the turn-of-the-century and being virtually complete by the mid-1920s. Residential structures pre-dating 1900 can be found on most streets in the neighbourhood. Churches, retail structures along Main Street, schools and other amenities have also been established through the years.
St. John's was part of the City of St. James when it became part of the City of Winnipeg which came into legal existence on January 1, 1972.
(taken from: the City of Winnipeg website)

Check out our extensive guidebook (below) for info on nearby (and not-so-nearby) places to check out during your stay!

neighborhood_overview:
Winnipeg's Exchange District is one of the most exciting and trendy neighbourhoods in Winnipeg. There is always something to experience. Stroll along the beautiful landscaped walkway on Waterfront Drive, explore some of the finest preserved historic architecture, or simply relax in Stephen Juba Park which is just steps away from the loft.
The Exchange District thrives today as one of Winnipeg's commercial and cultural centres, as well as an assortment of restaurants, nightclubs, and art galleries.
within walking distance you will find the Manitoba Theatre Centre (right across the street!) Planetarium, Science Gallery, Pantages Playhouse Theatre, Centennial Concert Hall, which houses the Royal Winnipeg Ballet, Symphony Orchestra, and the Manitoba Opera. The Goldeye's Baseball Stadium, Historical Forks, Children's Museum, and the Museum for Human Rights are only a short 10-15 minute walk. The MTS Centre which houses hockey games, concerts and other events is a 5 minute walk. On

neighborhood_overview:
St. John's is one of the more established neighbourhoods of the North End, its development occurring shortly after the turn-of-the-century and being virtually complete by the mid-1920s. Residential structures pre-dating 1900 can be found on most streets in the neighbourhood. Churches, retail structures along Main Street, schools and other amenities have also been established through the years.
St. John's was part of the City of St. James when it became part of the City of Winnipeg which came into legal existence on January 1, 1972.

neighborhood_overview:
St. John's is one of the more established neighbourhoods of the North End, its development occurring shortly after the turn-of-the-century and being virtually complete by the mid-1920s. Residential structures pre-dating 1900 can be found on most streets in the neighbourhood. Churches, retail structures along Main Street, schools and other amenities have also been established through the years.
St. John's was part of the City of St. James when it became part of the City of Winnipeg which came into legal existence on January 1, 1972.
(taken from: the City of Winnipeg website)

name: Riverfront character house with modern warmth
description:
This turn of the century character home is located facing the Red River in the historical neighbourhood of North Point Douglas.

Met by the bike trail (North Wpg Parkway, that leads to waterfront/ exchange district onto the forks).

Freshly updated while keeping the character and charm of exposed brick & millwork, this home is a perfect spot to unwind after a long day.

Generous master suite w/ walkin closet and ensuite bathroom, 2 additional bedrooms w/ river views , main bath w clawfoot tub.
neighborhood_overview:
Rich in history Point Douglas is one of Winnipegs earliest settlements. Barber house, Ross house Museum are both open for viewing in summer months.

This home offers significant history in itself. Situated in Winnipeg's first and only red-light district 1909-1912 and Purchased from the original family, this home was converted from a brothel, turned rooming house, duplex and now single family home.

*house is not haunted. Smudged by indigenous elder and blessed by a Christian minister*

Today North Point Douglas is a very diverse and rapidly changing neighborhood. Strong in activism, arts and indigenous culture the area has slowly battled a losing fight against gentrification. Surrounded on 3 sides by the red rier this neighbourhood offers beautiful views and easy accessibility to all the great things Winnipeg offers.

Only a few minute drive to The Forks/Human Rights Museum to fulfill your sightseeing needs. Or if you're feeling up to it, it's
host_about: We are Ben & Paige. Canadians that have explored most of North America, Asia, Europe and Africa. Looking forward to making new friends and experiencing different cultures along the way. Clean, friendly, polite, respectful. We have short and long term rentals in Winnipeg. Ben is a realtor/contractor and Paige is an interior designer that works in the movie industry.

As working professionals (Pilot/Teacher) and avid world travellers we love meeting new people, experiencing different cultures and exploring new places.  

We have travelled to over 30 countries; enjoying the cold of the Arctic, scuba-diving beautiful Ocean reefs, the jungles of Asia, and the mountains of Central America.

description: Turn of the century home with modern touches in mature quiet neighbourhood. This home offers original floors and millwork throughout the main floor.  This property is ideal for larger groups and construction crews. Longer term rentals welcome. Well maintained and freshly updated.
neighborhood_overview:
Rich in history Point Douglas is one of Winnipeg's earliest settlements. Barber house, Ross house Museum are both open for viewing in summer months.

This home offers significant history in itself. Situated in Winnipeg's first and only legal red-light district 1909-1912, this home was converted from what was once one of Winnipeg's most prominent brothels.

*house is not haunted. Smudged by indigenous elder and blessed by a Christian minister*

Today North Point Douglas is a very diverse and rapidly changing neighborhood. Strong in activism, arts and indigenous culture the area has slowly battled a losing fight against gentrification. Surrounded on 3 sides by the red river this neighbourhood offers beautiful views and easy accessibility to all the great things Winnipeg offers.

Only a few minute drive to The Forks/Human Rights Museum to fulfill your sightseeing needs. Or if you're feeling up to it, it's a beautiful 25 minute walk along the river
host_about: We are Ben & Paige. Canadians that have explored most of North America, Asia, Europe and Africa. Looking forward to making new friends and experiencing different cultures along the way. A nearby playground, just down the back lane, adds to the family-friendly appeal.

Our property has garnered numerous 5-star reviews from previous guests, praising its cleanliness, thoughtful amenities, and ideal location in the trendy South Osborne Neighborhood.

You are going to be staying in the South Osborne neighborhood and you couldn't have picked a better home base to discover many of the things that make this "one great city".
The neighborhood itself boasts many great restaurants and shops - check out hour guide book for a thoughtfully curated list of our favorite restaurants for specific occasions. Feel free to mention YOUR favorite in the review.

description:
A spacious lower level unit offering 2 bedrooms, spacious living and dining area, and beautiful finishes. We can assure this spot is your perfect home away from home.

Our goal is to ensure you are comfortable and feel at home during your stay. Our kitchen is equipped with stainless steel appliances and cookware to prepare a gourmet meal! Basic essentials are provided for you during your stay!

You're within walking distance to many great local shops and eateries.
neighborhood_overview:
St. Boniface is home to one of the largest francophone communities west of the Great Lakes, and it is the heart of Manitoba's French history and culture. While here, you can stroll along le boulevard Provencher and visit boutiques and quaint cafés along the way.

Gaining buzz in the French Quarter is Marion Street Eatery, which serves stylized comfort food for breakfast and lunch. Other notable eateries include: Resto Gare, where authentic French cuisine is served aboard a refurbished train car; Promenade Café and Wine with gorgeous views of The Forks and the downtown skyline; and Le Garage Café, which is constantly packed with live music lovers and is renown as one of the best poutines in the city.
Bookworms can head to À la Page for the largest selection of French books in the city, while chocolate lovers can satisfy a sweet-tooth at Chocolatier Constance Popp with artisan bon bons, bars, truffles, and more. Their chocolates make fantastic takeaway treats to give a

name: Cozy Bungalow Downstairs Suite
description:
The city of Winnipeg has changed the rules, so we only rent to clients for 30 days or more.
Our bungalow houses your basement suite. We are located in a residential area bounded by the river on 3 sides, and Osborne street on the west side. A 12 minute walk brings you to Osborne with grocery stores and restaurants.
We love to meet new people. (Unfortunately we cannot accept smokers.)
You will have an entire basement suite at your disposal. We live upstairs.
30 day min stay.
neighborhood_overview:
Our fully furnished bungalow is located in a quiet residential area bounded by the river on 3 sides, and Osborne street thoroughfare on the west. A 12 minute walk brings you to Osborne with grocery stores and restaurants. A 5 minute walk takes you to the river and a park with walks and cross country ski trails. Their is usually a skating path all the way to the forks in the winter. A 3 minute walk brings you to a bus stop.
Churchill Park is close by and makes for some wonderful walks through market gardens,and to our favorite ice cream shop. Fisher Park , a block of green is a block away as is our community center with tennis courts, outdoor BB courts etc.
host_about: Els and I enjoy meeting new people and have been doing AirBnb for a couple of years now. We both enjoy visiting Europe and especially Holland...since that is where Els was born.

neighborhood_overview:
Winnipeg's Exchange District stands as one of the most iconic and vibrant neighborhoods in the city. Designated as a national historic site, this area boasts an exceptional collection of heritage buildings constructed between 1880 and 1920. Fondly referred to as the “Chicago of the North,” the Exchange District showcases over 150 immaculate heritage buildings across a 20-square-block area. Once serving as warehouses and “terra cotta skyscrapers” housing financial institutions, these structures have now been transformed into Winnipeg’s cultural hub, flourishing with a diverse array of restaurants, galleries, gourmet donut and coffee shops, as well as hip clothing, lifestyle, and design stores.

Our loft, located in the heart of the Exchange District, offers an outstanding experience steps away from the river, with a beautiful walking and biking trail. It's a walker's paradise, where you can enjoy a pleasant stroll along the river for 10 minutes to reach Goldeye's Shaw Baseball
host_about:
" We travel the world over in search of what we need and return home to find it" 

As a little girl, I always admired the way a space and its’ contents have the ability to create memories and feelings. One of my earliest realizations of that experience was when my family and I spend a Christmas at a refugee camp when I was 10 years old. We had just escaped communism, leaving everything behind, yet my parents managed to create for us a lovely corner in our room with a small decorated Christmas tree, a bowl of nuts, some Mandarins, and even a few small presents. I still remember wondering how they managed to put this together for my sister and me? It was the loveliest feeling and that wonderful memory is still vivid in my mind as one of my very favorite Christmases. 

Perhaps it is this experience in leaving our life and all our worldly possessions behind to start again, which makes me always pause in a space and take in how it makes me feel. I truly believe in the wonder and emotional connection to the things that we choose to surround ourselves with. 

I have also been fortunate to put my head down on a pillow in many lovely places during my 20 years of executive global travel. I have come to appreciate that there are a few essentials that have always put a smile on my face and made me feel at home while traveling away from home. It is with this mindset that my family and I have approached the creation of this loft, our special space. 

A beautifully-appointed loft, with comfy bedding and linens, lovely amenities, all the comforts of home, and an opportunity to connect with locals, are but a few of the things that we hope our home and family can offer. We are passionate about our city and would love to share everything that may be of interest to you about Winnipeg. There is so much to discover and talk about in English, French, or Czech if you prefer.
We look forward to meeting you.

The neighborhood is adjacent to the Seasons of Tuxedo shopping district, featuring prominent destinations like IKEA, CF Polo Park, and a variety of upscale retailers. Nature lovers can enjoy the nearby Assiniboine Forest and FortWhyte Alive, which offer tranquil trails, wildlife viewing, and outdoor recreational activities.

You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

neighborhood_overview: Wolseley is a mixed neighbourhood of early 20th-century detached wood frame houses on elm-lined streets amid a scattering of small businesses and character apartment buildings. We are 5 minutes by bus or car, and less than 20 minutes on foot from downtown Winnipeg, the University of Winnipeg, Health Sciences Centre and Misericordia Health Centre. We are no more than 20 to 25 minutes by cab, bus or car from the University of Manitoba and most other destinations in the city. Several local grocery stores, coffee shops, bakeries, restaurants and other shops are within a 5-minute walk and major shopping is close by.
host_about:
We are two women living in a century home in the Wolseley neighbourhood in central Winnipeg. One designer and one carpenter by trade, we love collaborating on the restoration of this old house, making it a home for ourselves and a restful home-away-from-home for travellers.

We also enjoy travelling the world, and exploring rural North America in our vintage 1959 Sprite caravan.

Whether it’s in our home or on the road, we hope to see you soon!

Overview

The home is nestled in a tranquil and friendly neighborhood of Winnipeg, Manitoba. Its prime and well-connected location offer a relaxing retreat less than five minutes from the booming downtown.

One of the top attractions in Winnipeg is The Forks, a historic meeting place where the Red and Assiniboine Rivers come together. The Forks is home to various shops, restaurants, and events and is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike.

Other popular attractions in Winnipeg include the Manitoba Museum, which offers a glimpse into the province's natural and cultural history, and the Winnipeg Art Gallery, which features a collection of contemporary and indigenous art.

Winnipeg is also home to a thriving arts and culture scene, with numerous museums, galleries, and performance spaces. The city hosts several festivals annually, including the Winnipeg Folk Festival and the Winnipeg Fringe Theatre Festival.

neighborhood_overview:
Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

neighborhood_overview:
Rich in history Point Douglas is one of Winnipeg's earliest settlements. Barber house, Ross house Museum are both open for viewing in summer months.

This home offers significant history in itself. Situated in Winnipeg's first and only red-light district 1909-1912 and Purchased from the original family, this home was converted from a brothel, turned rooming house, duplex and now single family home.

*house is not haunted. Smudged by indigenous elder and blessed by a Christian minister*

Today North Point Douglas is a very diverse and rapidly changing neighborhood. Strong in activism, arts and indigenous culture the area has slowly battled a losing fight against gentrification. Surrounded on 3 sides by the red river this neighbourhood offers beautiful views and easy accessibility to all the great things Winnipeg offers.

neighborhood_overview:
Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

neighborhood_overview:
Location

The heart of Winnipeg's French community, St. Boniface is a historic neighbourhood with lots to offer. From culturally rich food, to quaint cafes to artisanal chocolate shops - a food lover will not be disappointed with what this area has to offer. After a bite to eat stroll the popular Provencher Boulevard that leads up to the elegant and beautiful Provencher Bridge. This bridge connects St.Boniface to downtown Winnipeg. 

Steps away from our rental are two of Winnipeg's biggest attractions - the Canadian Museum for Human Rights (CMHR) and The Forks. The CMHR is an architectural marvel and one of it's kind in Canada. The Forks is located at the junction of the Red and Assiniboine Rivers. It is a large community hub that offers shopping, dining, and recreational activities year round.

The playground is popular for its child sized zip-line, with view of airport planes taking off and landing, and the setting sun of in the distance.

Near the of the street on Ness Ave there is a fantastic pizza place named “Agostinos Pizzaria” that has a great lunch special, and offers a variety of hearty Italian meals. Also just west a few blocks over a city favourite burger place called “St James Burgers”,“Sam’s Corner” cafe/restaurant and a 7-11 where Ness meets Ferry Ave.

neighborhood_overview:
Winnipeg's Exchange District is one of the most iconic and vibrant neighbourhoods in Winnipeg. This national historic site features an exceptional collection of heritage buildings built between 1880 and 1920. Nicknamed the “Chicago of the North”, the Exchange features more than 150 immaculate heritage buildings within 20-square-blocks.

These buildings and tree-lined streets, which were once warehouses and “terra cotta skyscrapers” that housed financial institutions, have since become Winnipeg’s cultural hub, blanketed with restaurants, galleries, gourmet donut and coffee shops, hip clothing, lifestyle and design stores.

It’s also become the home to many Winnipeg businesses including graphic design and architecture firms, tech start-ups via Innovation Alley, and photography studios. Above the streets many of these older buildings’ floors have been converted into stylish studio apartments where a lot of the city’s hip set have started to migrate.

name: Exchange District NY Style Loft FREE PARKING
description:
This gorgeous brick and beam loft is located in the heart of Winnipeg's exchange district. It comes fully furnished and has everything you'll need for an exceptional stay.

We are in the theatre/waterfront east exchange district surrounded by:
Royal Manitoba Theatre Centre, Centennial Concert Hall, Manitoba Museum, the waterfront and river trail, Shaw Park stadium, The Forks Market, Canadian Museum for Human Rights - and of course, MANY amazing restaurants and pubs!
neighborhood_overview:
Winnipeg's Exchange District is one of the most iconic and vibrant neighbourhoods in Winnipeg. This national historic site features an exceptional collection of heritage buildings built between 1880 and 1920.
Nicknamed the “Chicago of the North”, the Exchange features more than 150 immaculate heritage buildings within 20-square-blocks.

These buildings and tree-lined streets, which were once warehouses and “terra cotta skyscrapers”, have since become Winnipeg’s cultural hub, blanketed with restaurants, galleries, gourmet donut and coffee shops, hip clothing, lifestyle and design stores.

It’s also become the home to many Winnipeg businesses including graphic design and architecture firms, tech start-ups and photography studios. Above the streets many of these older buildings’ floors have been converted into stylish studio lofts, like this one.

Nearby acclaimed dining includes: Deer+Almond with a menu that has graced several of Canada’s best restauran
host_about:
Hello/Bonjour, I am very excited to welcome and connect with our guests and earn your 5 star review...

I am a bilingual in French and English. Born in the Montreal area, I grew up living between both Quebec and British Columbia. I’ve also lived in Alberta, Ontario and now here in Manitoba. I’m excited to share Winnipeg’s best/most loved spots with you!

I’m a lover of music, sports, the arts, outdoors, mountain biking, travel, and my daughter. I have travelled to places throughout the world and are now looking forward to hosting you! I’m a firm believer in equality for all and welcome guests from all backgrounds.

name: in the heart of Corydon Village
description: When it comes to shopping and dining, Corydon Avenue aka Little Italy is one of the top destinations in the city - non ci piove! Here, you will find an eclectic array of local eateries and boutiques. Whether you spend a morning, afternoon or evening, there's plenty to uncover down this popular strip.
neighborhood_overview:
If you love nice patios, al fresco dining, gelato, and an all round jovial atmosphere, then Corydon Avenue is for you. Once known as Winnipeg’s “Little Italy,” Corydon Ave is a destination district, one which is popular with visitors and locals alike for people watching, shopping and dining. In the summer, you’ll find shady patios packed with people sipping sangria and beer. On Friday and Saturday nights during July and August, you’ll find a live music during the “Dancing on the Avenue” concert series featuring everything from 50s rock to jazz to blues.

A vast array of cuisines is available – from Japanese ramen, to Korean BBQ, to locally-sourced burgers, to sushi – while classic Italiano institutions serving gelati and strong shots of espresso are evident throughout. It’s also still the neighbourhood to go watch European sports, should the World Cup or Euros be on.

Corydon is also quite the shopping destination as trés chic shops now populate the avenue featuring

neighborhood_overview:
Nestled in one of Winnipeg's most mature neighborhood's and surrounded with things to do. Close to Corydon, Osborne Village, Polo Park Shopping Centre, Downtown and the Winnipeg Airport and surrounded by great places to eat and drink.

Corydon Avenue and Osborne Village have a great patio vibe in the summer and beautiful lights in the winter. We recommend Saffron's, Teo's and Carlos & Murphey's! There are also some fantastic coffee and dessert shops!

For families, Assiniboine Park Zoo is a MUST! There are many great animals to see and the polar bears make great entertainment! Take a stroll through Assiniboine Park afterwards, the duck pond is beautiful and there are plenty of walking paths and picnic spots!

neighborhood_overview:
St. Boniface is home to one of the largest francophone communities west of the Great Lakes, and it is the heart of Manitoba's French history and culture. While here, you can stroll along le boulevard Provencher and visit boutiques and quaint cafés along the way.

Gaining buzz in the French Quarter is Marion Street Eatery, which serves stylized comfort food for breakfast and lunch. Other notable eateries include: Resto Gare, where authentic French cuisine is served aboard a refurbished train car; Promenade Café and Wine with gorgeous views of The Forks and the downtown skyline; and Le Garage Café, which is constantly packed with live music lovers and is renown as one of the best poutines in the city.
Bookworms can head to À la Page for the largest selection of French books in the city, while chocolate lovers can satisfy a sweet-tooth at Chocolatier Constance Popp with artisan bon bons, bars, truffles, and more. Their chocolates make fantastic takeaway treats to give a

Gaining buzz in the French Quarter is Marion Street Eatery, which serves stylized comfort food for breakfast and lunch. Other notable eateries include: Resto Gare, where authentic French cuisine is served aboard a refurbished train car; Promenade Café and Wine with gorgeous views of The Forks and the downtown skyline; and Le Garage Café, which is constantly packed with live music lovers and is renown as one of the best poutines in the city.
Bookworms can head to À la Page for the largest selection of French books in the city, while chocolate lovers can satisfy a sweet-tooth at Chocolatier Constance Popp with artisan bon bons, bars, truffles, and more. Their chocolates make fantastic takeaway treats to give a

Corydon Avenue and Osborne Village have a great patio vibe in the summer and beautiful lights in the winter. We recommend Saffron's, Teo's and Carlos & Murphey's! There are also some fantastic coffee and dessert shops!

For families, Assiniboine Park Zoo is a MUST! There are many great animals to see and the polar bears make great entertainment! Take a stroll through Assiniboine Park afterwards, the duck pond is beautiful and there are plenty of walking paths and picnic spots!

neighborhood_overview: Spence is an eclectic, historic, sometimes gritty downtown neighbourhood. Like many downtown neighbourhoods in Canada, we have our share of traffic noise, homeless, and the need for street-smarts and common sense when on foot.

Overview

The home is nestled in a tranquil and friendly neighborhood of Winnipeg, Manitoba. Its prime and well-connected location offers a relaxing retreat less than five minutes from the booming downtown.

One of the top attractions in Winnipeg is The Forks, a historic meeting place where the Red and Assiniboine Rivers come together. The Forks is home to various shops, restaurants, and events and is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike.

Other popular attractions in Winnipeg include the Manitoba Museum, which offers a glimpse into the province's natural and cultural history, and the Winnipeg Art Gallery, which features a collection of contemporary and indigenous art.

Winnipeg is also home to a thriving arts and culture scene, with numerous museums, galleries, and performance spaces. The city hosts several festivals annually, including the Winnipeg Folk Festival and the Winnipeg Fringe Theatre Festival.

host_about:
Hi there!

We are so excited to host you during your stay! Being avid travelers ourselves, we love the experience AirBNB has provided being able to experience life as one of the locals in wherever we're going. We wanted to give the same experience to people visiting our properties and be able to provide the most incredible accommodations to all of our guests.

We obsess over every detail and have an incredible team to ensure our properties are cleaned and maintained to the highest standard prior to your visit. Our guests' book with us for a reason, and we'd love to host you for you to find out why.

Currently we are helping homeowners from across the country manage their investment properties / vacation rentals by welcoming guests into their homes through our property management business, Blue Bell Properties. We are a hands-on short term rental management company and handle all the logistical work that goes into managing short term rentals. Showcasing these properties to look their best and bring in higher returns for our partners and investors is just a small part of what we do.

If you like the idea of short term rentals, but simply don't want to handle the day to day management of dealing with guests, coordinating maid staff and maintenance, managing your calendar, and marketing your property to earn the highest nightly rates possible, feel free to contact us and we'd be happy to have a complimentary consultation with you and see if we are a good fit for your needs. We look forward to serving you and making your short term rental experience as hands off as possible and something you’ll love for years to come!

We hope you enjoy your stay with us and can experience everything our amazing properties have to offer!

One of the highlights of the Lord Roberts neighbourhood is the iconic pedestrian bridge that spans the Red River. The bridge offers stunning views of the river and surrounding landscape, and is a popular spot for walking, cycling, and taking in the scenery.

Nearby, you'll also find the famous Bridge Drive-In (BDI), known for its delicious ice cream and sweet treats. The BDI has been a Winnipeg institution for decades, and is a must-visit spot for anyone in the area.

In addition to these attractions, Lord Roberts offers several parks and green spaces of its own, such as McKittrick Park. These parks offer plenty of space for outdoor activities such as picnicking, sports, and leisurely walks.

description: Welcome home to this beautifully updated Tuxedo condo, located minutes from Assiniboine Forest, eateries and shopping!!! A bright & open space, 2 bedrooms with maple hardwoods. neighborhood_overview:
Tuxedo is Winnipeg’s “oh la la” area. Sprawling mansions, lush greenery and gorgeous character homes are found in this upscale suburban neighborhood. In the early 1900s Tuxedo was originally conceived as “Tuxedo Park,” an exclusive residential suburb.

Assiniboine Park is the area’s biggest attraction. This beautiful green space features a zoo, a duck pond, the Leo Mol Sculpture Garden, a new children's adventure playground area, Qualico Family Centre, trails, English gardens, restaurants, a pavilion and a stage for musical performances throughout the summer. The Park Café is warm, inviting and a picture-perfect place to have a meal with family and friends. Located inside the Qualico Family Centre, the child-friendly café is charming and affordable. If you want an up close and personal meeting with polar bears, then The Tundra Grill is sure to chill to the bone. This restaurant, located in the Assiniboine Park Zoo, offers exclusive views of playing polar bears while you dine.

neighborhood_overview:
Norwood Flats is a charming and family-friendly neighborhood located in the southern part of Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada. It is bordered by the Red River to the west, St. Mary's Road to the east, and the CNR Letellier Line to the south.

The neighborhood is known for its tree-lined streets, well-maintained homes, and beautiful green spaces. It is home to several parks, including the popular St. Vital Park, which features walking trails, picnic areas, and a large duck pond.

Norwood Flats is also known for its convenient location. It is situated just a short drive away from the downtown core and is easily accessible via several major highways. Additionally, the neighborhood is served by several bus routes, making it easy to get around without a car.

Residents of Norwood Flats enjoy a variety of amenities, including numerous shops, restaurants, and cafes. There are several grocery stores in the area, as well as a shopping mall and a movie theater.

neighborhood_overview: The Exchange District in Winnipeg is like stepping into a wonderful mix of the past and present. It welcomes you into a lively world of art galleries, theatres, and a buzzing arts scene. When it comes to food, you have plenty of choices, from cozy cafes to fancy restaurants that cater to all tastes. The district has many fun things to do, like theatres, live music spots, and places to hang out at night. If you enjoy shopping, you'll love the many unique stores and craft shops. It's also close to cool places like the Canada Life Centre and Human Rights Museum, which makes it even better. The Exchange District has a rich history, and its festivals and events celebrating art, culture, and community create a warm and welcoming atmosphere. Staying here gives you the perfect chance to experience Winnipeg's history, culture, and art while enjoying the modern comforts of the city. It's an open invitation to have a real and unforgettable Winnipeg experience.

description: Discover the heart of Winnipeg in this inviting hideaway. Situated in the vibrant downtown area, this stylish retreat immerses you in the city's rich cultural tapestry. neighborhood_overview:
Historic Charm: The Exchange District is known for its well-preserved architecture, featuring beautiful heritage buildings with distinctive facades. It’s often considered one of the best-preserved collections of turn-of-the-century commercial architecture in North America.

Cultural Hub: This area is a cultural hub, home to numerous art galleries, theatres, and cultural institutions. It’s a center for the arts in Winnipeg, with many festivals and events taking place throughout the year.

Dining and Entertainment: The Exchange District offers a diverse range of dining options, from cozy cafes to upscale restaurants. It’s also known for its nightlife, with bars, clubs, and live music venues.

Shopping: You’ll find unique boutiques, shops, and markets in the Exchange District, making it a great place for shopping and exploring local artisans.

neighborhood_overview:
The Forks:

This neighborhood is adjacent to The Forks, a historic meeting place at the confluence of the Red and Assiniboine Rivers, where you can find markets, dining, and entertainment.

Festival du Voyageur:

Saint Boniface hosts the Festival du Voyageur, Western Canada's largest winter festival, celebrating the region's fur-trading and Métis heritage.

Saint Boniface Cathedral:

The neighborhood is home to the iconic St. Boniface Cathedral, which is one of the city's most recognizable landmarks and has a rich history dating back to 1818.

Residents:

Several notable individuals, including author Gabrielle Roy and musician Daniel Lavoie, have called Saint Boniface their home.

Architecture:

You'll find a mix of architectural styles in Saint Boniface, from historic buildings to modern structures, creating a visually captivating environment.

neighborhood_overview:
Neighborhood Overview:
St. Boniface is known for its rich Franco-Manitoban heritage, and you'll find a strong cultural influence throughout the area. The neighborhood offers a mix of residential and commercial spaces, creating a dynamic environment that's both lively and tranquil.

Proximity to Hospitals:
For those seeking accommodation near the hospital, you're in the right place. St. Boniface is home to several healthcare facilities, including the St. Boniface General Hospital. This proximity can provide peace of mind for those who may need easy access to medical services.

Cultural Attractions:
St. Boniface is often referred to as the "French Quarter" of Winnipeg. It's home to several cultural attractions that showcase the neighborhood's rich history. The St. Boniface Museum, St. Boniface Cathedral, and Le Musée de Saint-Boniface are must-visit sites for those interested in the area's cultural heritage.

neighborhood_overview:
Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

Westwood is an established neighbourhood near Winnipeg's West Perimeter. There are over 10 parks south of Portage Avenue and Grant's Old Mill, Sturgeon Creek Park and Woodhaven Park within 3 km's. Walk along Assiniboine Avenue with several river access points to watch the Assiniboine River and frequently see deer and other wildlife.

Provides for an easy commute with quick access to neighbouring communites (Charleswood, St James, Polo Park, Wolseley) and is a 20 minute drive from Downtown, The Exchange, The Forks and St Boniface.

Winnipeg's Airport is 15 minutes away by car. There is frequent bus service along Portage Avenue with the 11, 21, and 22 which travel the length of Portage to Downtown, North on Main Street and the length of Henderson Highway (on the 11).

description: The whole group will enjoy easy access to everything from this centrally located place.
host_about:
I am  Canadian. I was born in Belgium to Italian parents from Abruzzi Italia. I am 66 years old, an electrical engineer now retired with 4 children and 6 grandchildren. I have many relatives in Rome and Abruzzi. I go to Italy every 2 years, usually in August, for the festivals and to visit family but not anymore; too hot! October now! I have many relatives that live in Rome and Abruzzi. I had an uncle in Rome who passed in 2016 at 107. 

Mexico is my second home. Mazatlan and Puerto Vallarta are my main destinations for Mexico . I spend one month there in Nov and 1 month in March. Most of my time is spent mainly in Mazatlan, where I own a condo,  to play tennis and then about  5 days in Puerto Vallarta to Salsa dance. It is the dolce Vita ( sweet life) ,sunny and day time temps of about +28.

I  enjoy hosting on Airbnb mainly because I like meeting new people and having people come from around the world. I use Airbnb whenever I can for traveling around the world because it is so affordable.   Dom and his wife Jessica live close by my home and are co hosts with my airbnb. 

Silvio

Cozy Private Room with Washroom.

Stay in a peaceful private room at North St Boniface! Perfect for solo travelers , this room features a comfortable double bed, washroom, high-speed WiFi.

neighborhood_overview:
located in the charming and historic neighborhood of North St. Boniface in Winnipeg. Known for its rich Francophone heritage, the area offers a unique blend of cultural vibrancy and peaceful residential living. Just steps away, you’ll find scenic walking paths along the Red River, picturesque parks, and local landmarks like Whittier Park and Fort Gibraltar.

The neighborhood is also home to delightful cafes, bakeries, and restaurants, many celebrating French-Canadian cuisine. With easy access to downtown Winnipeg and the Exchange District, North St. Boniface combines convenience with a welcoming community atmosphere. Perfect for those who appreciate history, nature, and a lively yet relaxed environment.

neighborhood_overview:
Located in the western part of the city, St. James is known for its family-friendly atmosphere, rich history, and accessibility to various amenities.

Key Features of St. James:
Shopping and Entertainment
St. James is home to CF Polo Park, Winnipeg’s largest shopping mall, featuring a wide range of retail stores, restaurants, and entertainment options. The area also boasts several smaller shopping plazas and independent boutiques.

Dining Options
The neighborhood offers a diverse culinary scene, ranging from local favorites to international cuisine. You’ll find cozy diners, trendy cafes, and family-friendly restaurants throughout the area.

Outdoor Spaces and Recreation

neighborhood_overview:
Stradbrook in Winnipeg offers residents proximity to a variety of notable attractions. These attractions provide residents with a rich blend of cultural, recreational, and social experiences, all within easy reach.

- Canadian Museum for Human Rights – A striking architectural landmark dedicated to the history and future of human rights.

- Winnipeg Art Gallery (WAG) – Features a vast collection of Canadian and international art, including the renowned Inuit art center, Qaumajuq.

- Assiniboine Park Zoo – A large zoo known for its Journey to Churchill exhibit, showcasing Arctic wildlife.

- Osborne Village – A lively neighborhood filled with unique shops, diverse restaurants, and vibrant nightlife.

- The Common at The Forks – A popular gathering spot offering craft beers and wines in a social, open setting.

Our mission is to provide overnight accommodations for business travelers in luxury, furnished apartments and serviced homes worldwide. 
Our standards demand that we select properties meeting our executive standards. 
As a global company, we combine our expertise with the local knowledge of our concierge staff who can assist you with any questions during your stay. Our committed team ensures that your stay is enjoyable, memorable, and stress-free from the time you book to the moment you check out. 
One of the most important goals is guest satisfaction. From booking to checkout, a team of dedicated concierges is present to insure your stay is enjoyable and up to standards.
